A Republican strategy to thwart Obama's reelection
Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to fight electoral fraud.
The Brennan Center, however, considers the latter a myth and claims that election fraud is less common in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
In fact, Republican lawyers have found no more than 300 cases of election fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the participation rate.
In that sense, these measures will undermine the American democratic system in part.
Unlike in Canada, the states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
And along that same lines, most of the American governments enacted, beginning in 2009, new laws that made it harder to register or vote.
This phenomenon has spread after the November 2010 elections, which saw the rise of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting voting rights were introduced in 41 states during 2011.
New election laws require voters to present a photo ID, plus proof of U.S. citizenship.
On the other hand, these laws reduce early voting periods, invalidate the right to register as an elector on election day and strip citizens with criminal records of their right to vote.
Before the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
The state of Indiana was the first to demand it.
The U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of the Indiana law in 2008.
So the Republican authorities were quick to extend the practice to other states.
In recent years these authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity document, such as a Social Security card.
In fact, 11 percent of American citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have any photo ID issued by a government agency in their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack an identity document with these characteristics.
But often the required ID costs more than a hundred dollars.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and people with low incomes.
Indeed, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000 a year, 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 do not have a photo ID.
And there's more.
In many states students, the voters who vote the most for Democratic candidates, cannot use their school's photo ID.
Moreover, those same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who usually vote for Republican parties to use documents issued by those clubs.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to make such a demand.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they're American citizens.
Those measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Hispanic vote.
It seems that two out of every three Hispanic voters support the Democratic Party.
On the other hand, Republican lawmakers backed in 2011 certain laws that abolished voter registration on the same day of the election in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to create a support service for voters who wanted to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns contributed to the registration of around 10 million citizens.
The measures taken since 2009 have resulted in the registration rate of new voters falling in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers passed laws in five other states that favored reducing the early voting period.
For example, in the 2008 election in Florida, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African-American, while the latter represented only 13% of the state's voters.
The same thing happened with the Hispanics.
These represent only 11% of the electorate, which is equivalent to 24% of the citizens who vote in advance.
However, whites, who make up 76% of the electorate, only make up 46% of citizens who vote in advance.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters have vehemently opposed the passage of laws restricting voter registration.
In this regard, Democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The U.S. Attorney's Office intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
The damage was partially contained.
For example, only 16 of 34 states passed legislation requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been voted on, as it is clear that they are intended to influence the 2012 results in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that states that have adopted such laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed in the Electoral College to win the presidency.
It is too early to say for sure whether these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the participation rate.
In this sense, the measures will undermine the American democratic system in part.
