The Higgs boson in detail
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson caused a great stir last summer, and rightly so.
It is believed, in fact, that this boson is part of the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
And what's more, it's the particle that the Standard Model predicted would exist -- our best or "least bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter, which has yet to be empirically observed.
But for physicists it's not entirely clear that it's the Higgs.
We know beyond a doubt that a new particle exists and that it closely resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
Furthermore, new data unveiled this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto seem to confirm that it is, although more data are still missing to be completely certain.
Anyway, we assume it's the Higgs, because the chances of getting it wrong seem low.
There is, in this great world, a general and inescapable law that implies that no two things can be in the same place at the same time.
There's no way you can break that rule and don't try too hard, because you'll end up hurting yourself.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been shown that it also has a law of this characteristic: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state"; a "state" that consists, roughly speaking, of some of their characteristics.
Physicists classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand, we find good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey Pauli's principle.
And on the other side are the bosons, a filthy gang of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means they can be in the same place at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure at Berkeley Laboratories, which is remarkable, bosons are divided into two groups: mesons, which we won't talk about here, and "force particles", which are the means by which the great forces of nature propagate and with which the Higgs boson is somehow related.
These bosons, I should stress here, are not the exotic bugs we might think.
In fact, if you can read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily common boson: the photon or "particle of light" that acts as a "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disrupts" the electromagnetic field in that precise environment - much like throwing a stone into a pond.
In this "disorder" an electromagnetic wave (from light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing more than a photon; that is, one of the "force-carrying" bosons.
More stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, except that it's another field, the Higgs field, that needs to be "disordered" for this boson to appear.
Now, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field, and to activate it you have to reach extremely high energies, kind of like an icy pond where just a thick rock could slide across the surface.
Therefore, a huge particle accelerator such as CERN (the large hadron collider is a 27 km ring!) is needed to reach such energy levels.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is a new tool that explains the relationship between the Higgs and mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never stick to a refrigerator door by itself.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have mass, while the rest (like the photon, by the way) don't.
What can all this research 'bring' to the table, asks Mrs Plamondon.
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the standard model (SM), and allows physicists to scrutinize differences between observations and predictions of the MS.
Many, in turn, eagerly look forward to meeting, for the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" that will fill certain gaps in the model.
This, it must be said, still has huge shortcomings, such as not proposing any explanation regarding gravity (ups!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter in the Universe (another ups!).
But we haven't found such differences at CERN so far.
The impact
The impact of such research on our daily lives is difficult to predict, but we do not think we are wrong to say that it will have none.
So, you see, in the early 1960s, the laser pioneers in the laboratories had no idea what a revolution their work would bring.
They saw the scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, as physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962, said, at first the laser was rather considered a "laboratory device".
Can you imagine?
And furthermore, applications can also come from all the instruments surrounding research.
For example, Willard Boyle himself developed a light detector in 1969 during his research into optics.
Although it was not at all his original intention, this sensor now serves as the "eye" for all the digital devices in the world, earning him the Nobel Prize in physics in 2009.
That's not to say, of course, that the activities of the LHC necessarily want to transform our lives, but you never know...
