With Bitcoin, pay and sell without banks
This is in contrast to current monetary exchanges, which are based on central banks, identified transactions and processing burdens between parties.
Moreover, as is often the case in technology, the political vision is palpable: the conviction that the current monetary system, made up of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency convertible to dollars, euros, etc. and a secure exchange protocol like BitTorrent, which allows for peer-to-peer file sharing.
Nearly 200,000 transactions have been recorded from 15,000 computers in the network.
And about a thousand websites accept bitcoins as donations or as a form of payment.
The bitcoin price, after reaching a high of $30 in June 2011, fell to $2 five months later, before returning to around $10 today (the prices are counted on the bitcoincharts.com page).
It is not impressive when compared with global changes in real currency or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) became interested in it in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
In it, bitcoin was described as "the most successful virtual currency", "competing with the dollar or the euro" and "similar to conventional currencies".
Bitcoin differs from other systems with types of virtual currencies such as "credits", used to advance a video game and which can be earned by playing or can be bought (and even sometimes redeemed).
The social network Facebook also developed this type of system.
But in every exchange, a central authority controls and handles the changes.
With bitcoin, all network nodes are at once bookkeepers, verifiers, coin issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does that network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually done between two e-mail addresses.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus guaranteeing anonymity.
A set of information linked to this transaction is signed electronically via a double-key encryption system.
The network can then verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the changes in bitcoins are recorded in the public ledger, which is disseminated throughout the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction in that ledger.
It involves solving a mathematical challenge thrown at computers and the winner, a sort of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
It is a file-shredding phase, i.e. transforming a large file into a shorter, unique numerical footprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number before "slicing" the set.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular trace (more zeros at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it's the right one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of sets of the other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, to commit fraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept as valid one of the two transactions; the other would be orphaned, as both have different footprints.
The computer that solves the challenge gets 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, that reward is split in half regularly, most likely before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible by one hundredmillionth, leaving a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in each increase in computing power.
Life on the net has its ups and downs.
Websites that offer services for Bitcoin have been hacked and bitcoins in storage have been stolen.
"The fault used does not affect the same protocol", says Pierre Noizat, who just launched Paymium, a real-money payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also takes into account the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash has the same flaw.
Big players like Wikipedia reject payments of this kind.
Others, like the WordPress platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, of the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the ledger and showed that about 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November, the "giant sales" were launched.
"$30,000 was changed", rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, author of a pedagogical book on the currency, believes strongly in the potential of this technology in addition to the transaction network.
Their system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or contactless mobile payment, but uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which are cheaper.
The bearer also manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system is easy to set up in shops, which do not have to install new terminals or software.
They simply provide an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize", says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement to revise hierarchical systems for more horizontal systems.
"It will take a while for Bitcoin to gain traction, but in 2013 there could be a change", he predicts.
The ECB also plans to reassess the various risks, which are now considered high, if the currency succeeds.
