A Constitution with Forceps in Egypt
He's a new double or nothing for President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever over the constitutional declaration, which provisionally grants it full powers, he decided to play the whole for the whole.
He took everyone by surprise on Wednesday, when he announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Only a week ago the Head of State gave the Assembly two months to finish its work.
And for almost two years now, Egypt has been using a provisional text, amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to judicial turmoil.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the president persists in his "autocratic delusion" and continues to "betray his word" and "trample on the law".
The Commission has also been asked to submit a proposal for a directive on the protection of workers from the risks related to exposure to ionising radiation.
A referendum should be held within the next 15 days.
A very short time that forced the Brethren to abandon their project of explaining the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy while the controversy is wreaking havoc across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that Egyptians will vote for him, as he claimed in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Considering that the appeal was voted on very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "either vote my text or I keep the full powers", powers that will supposedly come to an end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in this strange environment that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, the vast majority of whom are Islamists, voted on the text yesterday.
Most of the liberals didn't go to the call.
In mid-November, just before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they felt they could not assert their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 people were added yesterday morning, substitute members, in a hurry.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
As expected, the votes were unanimous.
The commentators are amused, moreover, by the fact that one of the few discrepancies of the day was expressed practically at prayer time, so much so that several members of the committee came to think that the Constituent Assembly's clock was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on yesterday afternoon, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, the object of all eyes, remains ultimately identical to the 1971 Constitution, which stipulated that "the principles of Sharia constitute the principal source of law".
Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental demand, hoped that "principles" could be replaced by "norms", which would have allowed for stricter enforcement.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
The Liberals call it hypocrisy and consider it nothing more than a publicity stunt.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer in particular to Article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University a consultative role, in particular for anyone who has to confirm its compliance with Sharia law.
According to Egyptologist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because "people called to speak are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we glimpse the premises of a theocracy".
The fears of the liberals are further heightened by the fact that the next rector of the university would be considerably less moderate than the current one.
"At this time, there is no specific religious implication.
With this Constitution we are in the framework of the civil status.
Most of the jurists who have worked on this text are not ulama but university students, some of them trained in the French system", explains Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that there may be some ambiguity about Article 220, since the terms used mimic religious vocabulary.
"We are referring specifically to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence].
And the question that might arise in the future would be to what extent are civil judges competent to rule above all this".
The text voted yesterday has received much criticism, apart from its religious character, for the extensive powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood will claim that they are few in number compared to those who were under the previous regime.
Another point of contention: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the review of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Nor will the prosecution of civilians in military courts be prohibited, as called for by human rights associations.
The Commission has also expressed its concerns about the text, which it considers liberticidal.
The crime of blasphemy remains and insults are henceforth prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially that of the press.
Moreover, no article emphasizes the protection of women, stresses Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
The only positive thing, she said, was the prohibition of torture under Article 36.
The word was not in the previous Constitution.
Although the Egyptian president was scheduled to appear on television last night, demonstrations are expected this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state demonstrated on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are waiting for the holy land, the navel of the world and a sea of brine
The Promised Land combines the majesty of Bible truths with modern comforts and pristine nature.
"AIF" identified the five most important reasons why one should visit Israel.
Reverence in the Holy Land
The Jordan River, where Jesus was baptized, is worth a visit.
It is believed that anyone who enters this "baptism pile" will receive divine grace.
And Galilee, the place of Jesus' miracles: turning water into wine at a wedding, walking on water, calming a storm and filling nets.
It was at this same place that Jesus appeared to his disciples after his resurrection.
But the greatest number of holy places are in Jerusalem.
Believers walk here the Viacrucis or the Way of the Cross of Jesus (in Latin "Via Dolorosa").
It begins at the Fortress of Anthony, the Praetorium, where the trial was held, and continues through the streets of the Old City, going to the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha, the place of the crucifixion, to the Stone of Unction and the place of Jesus' burial.
In this same place is also the symbolic Christian Navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
And the Monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem, built on the spot where, according to Christian legend, there was a tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus.
Jerusalem is also home to the holiest site for Jews, the Western Wall, the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 C.E.
As is tradition, people of different religions leave notes here with their wishes, which will then come true.
Take a vertical trip
The ruins of Masada Fortress were what remained of a secret refuge from enemies, which Herod the Great had built in 25 B.C. for his family.
They are located on mountain cliffs at an altitude of 450 m above sea level.
And to get there on their own, only those who are dedicated to climbing can.
The rest of you can reach this historic summit by funicular.
And in the north of the country at an altitude of 1600-2040 m is the famous Hermon ski resort, where in the winter months there is a large influx of tourists.
Bus services run from the foot of the hill.
The total length of the ski slopes is 45 km.
According to an ancient legend, the mountain was supposed to be the abode of pagan gods.
