There are about 300 museums in this country.
You won't be able to visit them all in one trip.
But at least five of them are worth visiting, the most interesting ones.
Among them is the Israel Museum, located near the Knesset (Israeli Parliament).
It contains the ancient Dead Sea Scrolls or Qumran Scrolls, discovered in caves in the Judean desert, and about 500,000 archaeological and anthropological pieces.
The Tel Aviv Museum of Art is worth a visit.
In his exhibition of paintings he has canvases of impressionists and expressionists such as Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall or Picasso.
In Acre you can visit the Al Basha Museum-Bath, which are some rooms of ancient Turkish baths with model figures of visitors and bathers of that time.
In Caesarea, you can visit the exclusive private Ralli Museum, where you can admire the sculptures of Rodin and Dalí.
There are no tourist guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free, and donations are strictly not accepted.
The fifth, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, shows one of the most dramatic pages in history.
The most tragic section is the Children's Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children murdered in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You walk into it and you're in complete darkness.
The stars are shining.
And the names of the Jewish children ring out and the names of the countries where they lost their lives.
Ukraine is mentioned as well.
Health
The three main tourist areas of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
Each of these has swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums, and oceanographic museums.
It is interesting that in the Red Sea they bathe even in the winter months, since the water temperature does not drop below 70 degrees Fahrenheit [21°C] and the air warms up to 90 degrees Fahrenheit [23°C].
The Dead Sea is even warmer and bathing is done there all year round.
By the way, this sea, the most extraordinary in the world, is located at the lowest point on the planet: at 417 meters below sea level.
The blue waters there are a brine that easily holds even those who cannot swim.
The surrounding landscapes are truly beautiful.
People come here to undergo courses of saltwater, brine, and mud therapy to fortify their health in cases of dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes, and to put their broken nerves in order.
Touching the mysteries of antiquity
They are preserved in the old part of Tel Aviv, the citadel of Jaffa, on the Mediterranean coast.
It was the famous sea route linking Egypt, Syria, Anatolia, and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark and Perseus rescued the beautiful Andromeda with whom, in this same place, he led a long and happy life.
Tourists love to stroll along the narrow streets named after the signs of the Zodiac.
They say if you touch the walls on the street with your "own" symbol, fortune will be favorable to you.
In Jaffa you can find newlyweds who come from all over Israel, and even from other countries to take pictures.
And in Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can walk around the Roman theater, "take" the fortress of the crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the chief city of Judea and the residence of Roman procurators, including Pontius Pilate.
The theatre, carefully restored, is now used for night concerts and opera performances.
