While MPs and human rights defenders debate the consequences of the law on compulsory examination, fraudsters who trade in "fake" certificates have already appeared in the country
Each year, 13 million migrant workers arrive in Moscow, St. Petersburg and other cities in Russia.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asian countries: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money to help their families who have stayed home.
From 1 December a law comes into force, according to which every migrant worker must take an exam to check his knowledge of Russian.
For now, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the service sector, community service institutions, domestic services and retail trade.
However, in time, as promised by the Federal Immigration Service, the tests will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, it will not be enough to pass the language exam, but also the Russian history and the fundamentals of legislation.
Language skills must also be confirmed for the purpose of obtaining and renewing a work permit.
The exception is citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
The law does not apply to persons who obtained their education certificates and diplomas before the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991.
Usefulness, fatality and defence of rights
The network of examination centres will be operated under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute of Russian Language, the Peoples' Friendship University, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Immigrants will be able to come to the tests in all cities, right now in Russia there are more than 160 such centers open.
The initiative to introduce the exam was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Immigration Service.
But rights advocates, long before the law came into force, often managed to ask the press this question: What will this really do?
What changes will the compulsory knowledge of the language bring, both for Russians and for immigrants themselves?
First, the immigration service replies, this will reduce the number of people who suffer "labor slavery".
Many people today talk about defending the rights of migrant workers, explains Victor Sebelev, head of the Russian Federal Immigration Service's representation in Tajikistan.
The defence of your rights must begin before you leave.
Only an organised selection system will solve the problem of migrant workers in 90% of cases.
The problems are with immigrants without a profession, without education, without language skills and without medical examination.
Without understanding the language, says Sebelev, the future immigrant will be condemned to encounter unscrupulous people who, under the guise of helping, put him on a "paid trip" to a creepy, narrow covacha, where he and dozens of others like him are consumed for months without food or papers, working 12 to 14 hours a day.
We've had countless complaints from our immigrants.
"In their homeland they are promised something, but when they arrive they are deceived, they are deprived of their passports, they are not paid the promised salaries", confirms the Head of the Labour Immigration Directorate of Tajikistan's Immigration Service, Tolib Sharipov.
Don't get mad, little chief!
Meanwhile, however, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who wish to work in Russia admit that they not only do not know the language of the country to which they intend to go, but also have difficulty writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as their own misfortune: few Turkmen, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to receive a normal primary education.
This is because their families have nothing to feed their children, let alone clothe, shoe, and buy them school supplies.
When they reach their teens, these kids venture into work at the first opportunity.
It's hard, if you don't know the language, they recognize you.
"You feel humiliated and inferior".
However, when it comes to the language law, rights advocates point out an important point.
The examinations will be conducted only for those immigrants whose status is legal.
If they don't have that status, there won't be any exams and, consequently, no official work.
Meanwhile, most migrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or no strangers allowed"
Many visitors claim that receiving official status in our country is not so easy.
The cause lies in bureaucratic obstacles and in the difficulties of the language itself.
In addition, legalization costs money: from twelve thousand to sixteen thousand rubles.
However, a false registration can be made quickly and for only 1,500 rubles.
Russian police employees know that we usually carry false documents, we are not registered and extortion cases appear.
"They ask us for a hundred or two hundred rubles for cigarettes or tea", Tajik citizen Umed Hushkadamov told reporters.
"Come on, don't be stingy, buy a painting"
On the first day of the language law's entry into force, it became clear that not only immigrant registration documents can be forged.
Several "fake" certificates of language proficiency have already been seized by Federal Immigration Service officials.
The forged documents had been printed on standard color printers.
Of course, they did not reach the new owners as a gift: each immigrant, wanting to facilitate the task of passing the tests, paid for the document seven thousand rubles.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official examination procedure, which will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
The main task for the near future is to protect the system against corruption so that "diplomas" cannot be bought, converge government officials and rights advocates.
So far, the authorities can promise migrant workers who failed the test the first time more time to study the basic language course.
In addition, non-Russian-speaking immigrants will be offered jobs that do not require active communication with people.
