"For now, fooling the brain is not so easy".
The topic of augmented reality, so popular among modern technology enthusiasts, is lately normally perceived mainly through the prism of special glasses.
In early summer, at its annual conference, Google demonstrated a moving model and later in November, it became known that Microsoft had also filed an application to claim the corresponding patent.
However, a conversation with the head of the interactive 3D technology group at Microsoft's Cambridge lab, Izadi Sharamom, revealed that for the company's scientists, glasses were already a thing of the past.
They are attracted to the prospect of manipulating virtual objects in the air with bare hands and creating open virtual spaces.
- Please, in general terms, what is the subject of your research group?
- We're dedicated to human-computer interaction, but we also try to push the boundaries of this interaction.
For now humanity in its mass has been stuck in the stage of working with the pixels of the flat screen, sometimes touching it with your finger.
But we want to look five to 10 years ahead and guess the cardinal changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors represent a step forward and nowadays no Xbox is sold without Kinect, as everyone is interested in gesture control.
- What else does the future hold?
- Even though Kinect has brought interaction to the physical level, much of it still happens on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information has improved (the system receives more data), and the output is still not very good.
We're trying to change that, we're working on truly three-dimensional visualization systems, based on different technologies, including design ones.
We must free the world from the computer to ours, to the physical, to make it more tangible.
For this, however, it is necessary to recognize not only the user but also the space around him.
Then we can complete the real world with virtual objects in a more comfortable way.
First of all, to hell with those stupid VR headsets!
- What do you think about voice control?
A very popular detail, but don't you think they're overestimating it?
- Of course you can't consider it a panacea, it's pending to resolve the issue of privacy, since you don't always want others to know about your actions and intentions.
In fact, all kinds of computer interaction are good, but each in its own field.
For example, for controlling devices in public places, we had a project where we thought about gestures, but not loose movements, but shorter ones.
In addition, gestures were captured not by the device's camera but by a bracelet that recorded the movement of bones and muscles.
It's pretty big for now, but in theory it can be scaled down to the size of a wristwatch.
But, in general, the future is for a combined type of control, for example gesture + voice.
- What's that? - What?
- For example, how would you ask me to pass this can of soda?
You will speak and show it at the same time.
- I usually just talk.
- Oh, that's gonna be very hard to recognize.
- So you want to force users to adapt to what the machine can or cannot do at this time?
- Not necessarily, but it's a mutual approach.
I think in the near future we're going to have to work primarily on designing new types of sensors that can accurately determine a person's reactions.
These can be, for example, laser sensors, because they provide good resolution in depth, which is very important.
- Speaking of your work with Xbox Kinect sensors, what are your complaints about modern cameras?
Do you lack resolution, depth or something else?
- In principle, the current generation is what may be the beginning of our work with three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, it would be nice to get 8 megapixels at 1000 fps.
But the question is not megapixels, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
From this latter point of view, all current technologies are not good enough for us; this gives more work to algorithm designers.
So we have to remember not only the resolution on the X and Y axes, but also on the Z axes.
Speed is also important, the number of frames per second.
Human movements are quite dynamic and current at 30 fps is really sparse, especially for gestures.
Steven Bathiche, from our lab in Redmond, made a contact sensor with an adjustable processing delay of 1 to 100 ms and it is worth mentioning that modern mass-produced sensors are closer to the second value (60-100).
Not everyone understands the extent to which this affects human-machine interaction.
I would find it very useful for my work to have an equivalent of such a device, but one that does not require contact to make frames per second more.
- And don't we need to increase the number of cameras?
- The Kinect now has three "cameras", one of which is actually the infrared emitter and the second the reflected signal receiver.
But the third camera is actually a simple sensor of the visible tuning fork.
This is not used to determine the depth of the object.
Potentially, more cameras could solve the problem...
Or, on the contrary, increase it and increase the required amount of calculations.
It would be nice to create a flexible Kinect analogue, play with the camera's position curve and see how this would help determine the three-dimensional position.
- As I recall, Microsoft, unlike Google, has not introduced its glasses to the public.
Do you not think that, from the point of view of everyday use of augmented reality technologies, glasses are one of the most visible platforms?
- Of course, spending all the time holding a smartphone high in your hands, it's not very comfortable, but I think: the best option would be a "transmutable" augmented reality when, based on a cloud platform, you could switch from glasses to a smartphone,
Glasses are very personal devices, that's their strength (private things only you can see), but also their weakness: an augmented reality based on glasses won't allow you to work on virtual objects together with other people.
- Let's imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in mid-air is available not only to Tony Stark from the movie "Iron Man", but also to any mere mortal.
There is a problem with this idea that critics often point out: there is no tactile response!
The hands feel nothing!
What responses does your group prepare for this challenge?
- In my lectures I often say that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in human-machine interaction.
I think the eighth might well be the addition of tactile sensations.
Meanwhile, one of the most interesting tricks is using the second hand as a support for the image.
It records touch perfectly!
But there are also technologies that are really geared to bring tangibleness to these "images in the air". For example, the interference of several ultrasonic rays directed at a specific point where the finger is, gives a sensation similar to what you feel if someone is blowing on your fingertips, but that sensation is still very weak.
There are also wristbands that influence the nerve endings of the fingers, which is also a promising direction.
- Have you tried to fool the brain?
Make him think that he feels what he seems to feel the moment he sees something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried it yet.
Here is another challenge that we will have to fight for a long time, how to make a person physically located in a very small space believe that he is going to an open, almost endless space.
For now, fooling the brain is not so easy, it still has many years to work.
That's what makes working with virtual reality so attractive to researchers, that a lot of things are in a state of total conception.
