NKÚ chief: Inspection of "švarc" system has not found the guilty politician
The Czech Republic has good public procurement inspectors and quality legislation, although its implementation is lagging.
This is stated by Miloslav Kala, vice president of the Supreme Control Office (NKÚ) in an interview with Aktuálně.cz.
"The law will never be perfect", but its application must be correct. "This is what I think we are lacking", he describes the current situation.
The joint inspections by the Czech and German inspectors also come to similar conclusions.
As an example of a wrong practice, he mentions Petr Nečas' attitude towards the system of being autonomous only on paper, which is known as the "švarc" system.
The Prime Minister recently said that the ODS (Civic Democratic Party) would not bother businessmen with inspectors.
"The law must be regulated in some way and if it prohibits something, in that case, neither the president of the government can prevent the office from acting that has the obligation to perform those controls or demand obligations", Kala says.
At the meeting of the Control Committee in the Congress of Deputies you spoke of the joint project between the Czech and German teams, in which the legislation on public procurement in both countries was compared.
What is it exactly?
This is a parallel monitoring that we started doing about two years ago.
In simple terms, European legislation regulates how public procurement should be organised, followed by national legislation and then the practice itself.
We have put everything together and, although the control has not yet been completed, we have obtained very interesting differences.
It is therefore confirmed that it is not enough to introduce ever stricter rules, but that it is necessary to concentrate on the application of the law itself.
What can this project actually bring? What do you think are the conclusions?
It is precisely this kind of common control that could help us to stop investing in the efforts to make laws more concrete, to reduce and improve the limits, even if this does not have such a positive impact.
The economy of savings means getting a suitable thing at a reasonable price (which does not always mean that the price is the lowest) to avoid enrichment and, in the long run, criminal actions.
But the fact that we are reducing the limit on the number of awards does not mean that we are going to achieve it.
Perhaps because the system is saturated with so much paperwork, those who want to look for flaws in the system will be able to do so more easily than if the limits were kept as high as they are now.
You speak of the problems of our country with the transfer of legislation regulating the practice of public procurement.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is it an office similar to our NKU or is it organized differently?
As far as the offices are concerned, such as the NSC, there is the Bundesrechnungshof (Federal Court of Auditors), with a similar organization to ours, with a college too, only that in this case it is structured in a somewhat different way, but in principle both offices are evolving in parallel.
The powers are also somewhat similar, but while Germany has a federal organisation, the audit courts are even at this level.
The Federal Court of Accounts (BRH) can only control federal money, what we here call state funds.
Public funds, which are managed by the regions and municipalities, are controlled in Germany by the Federal Court of Auditors.
As for the local legislation, is it simpler than ours?
I would not normally like to make a comparison without specific data, but Germany is still a model in some respects, but it is not possible to say exactly which is better.
Could it be better, for example, in terms of the quality of inspectors?
I'm sure not, but, again, I don't like to make these kinds of comparisons.
It is necessary to say that even those countries which we take as models have to face a large number of problems.
If it wasn't, you wouldn't have any benefit from working with our office, would you?
As far as the legislation of our country is concerned, what did the amendment to the law on public procurement mean for your Office?
Given the relatively short period of validity of this amendment, it has not yet been implemented in the control procedures.
Since we carry out ex post checks, we must expect a certain delay.
The Commission has already started a new tool for the detection of non-economic risks, which has been used to screen almost 14 000 public tenders, and which will be perfectly reflected here, as the limits are changed, the conditions for some types of selection process are rectified and the like.
Do you consider that the passing of this law is beneficial or rather a tangle for the bureaucratic system?
I think this law is certainly a step in the right direction and I hope it is.
The problem that can arise is that the regulations "get harsher" and it becomes impossible to comply with them.
Under the previous rules, the persons subject to control were already linked to the contractor (for example, in the case of the regional operational programmes of the regional council), and any law on public procurement not respected was a breach of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense then to tighten the law this way?
I don't think it's like this.
The system must exclude those who want to attack or take advantage of it and not punish those who commit a formal ruling, which has no impact on decision-making.
A system of this kind will only create more bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We'll see where this path we've started takes us.
The Prime Minister has recently stated that the SDG would not bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called švarc system, referring to being self-employed only on paper.
Is the "Svarc" system prohibited or allowed?
