Šimon Ornest: In our concerts we want to accumulate positive energy
They say the world will end in a little less than a month, what do you think?
It's just one of many other alarmist news stories we like to cling to.
The Tap Tap band likes to joke about this and we like to say that we are the only band in the world that can muster enough positive energy to postpone the end of the world or to prevent it.
In December, you're organizing a really original project: three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you explain that to our readers?
This is a state benefit we've been planning for two years.
We decided to take advantage of the marketing potential that the end of the Mayan calendar had for December 21 at 11:10 in the morning.
The day before, December 20 at 9 pm, we will be holding 3 simultaneous concerts in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
They will end at about the same time as the Mayan calendar ends on the Pacific island of Kiribati, 12 hours ahead of our time zone.
Whose idea was this?
It was my idea at first, then we went on to forge the project together with our designer Honza Augusta.
In addition to wanting to gather enough positive energy and prevent the end of the world, we also want to reflect, together with society, on the state in which we will leave the world to our children.
To mark the end of the Mayan calendar, we have also created a unique collection of items: boots, T-shirts, bags and original doomsday keys that can be purchased at www.e-tap.cz, another way to support us.
The Tap Tap group, along with other performers, also sang the so-called anti-doomsday anthem, titled "End of the World, Cancelled".
It's currently very popular on YouTube, can you hear it at the benefit concerts?
Of course I do, and it'll be just the last, well, as long as everything goes well and the world doesn't end...
It will be sung by all the performers at the same time in all three concerts.
The anthems will be linked together simultaneously thanks to a special live broadcast on Czech Television.
Tomáš Hanák has written the lyrics to this song and plays the lead role of Jesus in the music video, where he also sings Xindl X...
How did this collaboration come about?
We even work together with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, apart from organizing many charity events and concerts...
We put all our efforts into this project.
Most of them have shown interest and enjoyment in working with us.
What will the money raised from the doomsday concerts be used for?
To equip the barrier-free educational centre Studeo, which we are completing for the sixth consecutive year with the civil association Tap in Jedličkův ústav.
Students at Jedličkův ústav school are regularly visited by teachers with whom they have fun and interesting activities.
Students do not have sufficient financial means to pay teachers and we make an effort to make this possible.
As part of the completion of the works at Jedličkův ústav, there will be an independent building to which we will move with this project.
At each concert, several groups and performers perform.
What are the selection criteria?
We try to develop a program that is appealing to all generations, including children.
For example, in Prague, Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý will perform.
For more information, please visit www.kpks.cz.
Do you have any other similar "spectacular action" planned in the future?
In May we will perform for the first time at the Prague Spring festival, so here we will surely prepare an attractive program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to play at the Bohemian National Hall in New York and I, personally, taking advantage of being in the United States, would like to complete it with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your plans abroad are not exactly minimalist, so far you have performed for example in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap is, however, a group made up of people with disabilities.
How is the logistics and organization of these trips?
It's not as difficult as it may seem at first glance.
There are five members in electric wheelchairs, the chairs have to travel in the luggage compartment and we also carry a lot of weight, the boxes with the instruments...
However, we have managed to do well so far.
Even in Moscow, where we just returned from, everything went smoothly.
Excursions abroad allow you to compare different attitudes towards disabled people and other aspects of society.
What have you encountered so far?
In Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities, everything works better than here; in Russia we have seen that there is still a long way to go in the East.
Unlike Prague, Moscow is full of barriers, where it is still rare for a person to travel alone through the city centre in an electric wheelchair.
Something as common as, say, giving preference to someone in a wheelchair in an elevator, it's not there.
Fortunately, a civil association has been set up to address the problems of people with disabilities.
In what ways should we follow the example of more advanced countries?
There are many aspects in which we are behind...
But it is important to mention that the improvement and improvement of the situation always depends on the people directly affected.
In London and Madrid it is quite normal for people with severe disabilities to move about on their own in public and can go to the toilet, to the museum, wherever they want...
But it is not very common for a large number of people with disabilities to participate in social life in an active way, in this respect, with The Tap Tap we are a little ahead!
A respectful or barrier-free society is one thing, but when the time comes when eminent athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers emerge, everything will start to change for real.
So far, these are isolated cases of people who have great willpower.
The Tap Tap is very popular right now, but if we look back a few years, what led you to form the group in 1998?
I entered as an educator in Jedličkův ústav, where I had many young people around me who wanted to devote themselves to something.
And since I'm a musician, I play, among other things, the saxophone, I founded an amateur group with a coworker.
And over time, as our moderator Láďa Angelovič says, it got a little out of hand. (Laughter)
However, popularity did not come until recent years, am I wrong?
It's true that connecting with famous singers and also working actively to promote the group helped us a lot.
We came to the conclusion that work that is not seen is as if it did not exist.
Thanks to the European Union's aid, we can afford quality teachers, equipment, etc.
Did you intend to go this far with The Tap Tap?
I saw the potential from the beginning, that you could do something differently.
The show business is full of things that look alike.
It is logical, in its own way, that everything new is greeted with caution and takes a long time to be accepted.
There are few extraordinary things, but I dare say The Tap Tap is one of them.
The impression of someone who sees us for the first time is clearly compassion, it's a natural reaction...
But compassion is totally superfluous because people with disabilities are not abandoned, suffering beings that we should have compassion for.
There are people who are able to live a full life and develop themselves, provided, of course, that they have the necessary means.
I always say that if something goes well for people with disabilities, then it's not just a breakthrough for them, but for the whole society.
Did it help that you're a demanding boss, as many people describe you?
If we want to do quality work, we have to be rigorous in many respects and demand a certain amount of discipline.
I think it's completely normal.
Some people come with a romantic vision and their heads in the clouds and when they find out they have to come for two days to rehearse, go to the prep test and spend a lot of time traveling and at concerts, the initial euphoria quickly leaves them.
But that's how it works everywhere, in every group that wants to work and achieve something.
The Tap Tap currently has twenty members.
How many of them were there at the beginning of 1998?
There's only one, Ladja Angelovic.
We're an open group, people come and go, you can't help it.
