The architectural studio MVRDV shows that true adventures are not just in the head - in the example of the Spijkenisse library and the recently completed "mountain of books"- 2 photos
"I think the building is fun, it looks futuristic, and there is finally something interesting to see", says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT technician at a large company near the library, points out: "Besides, the building is beautiful".
But I wonder why we need a library today.
We all have the Internet, tablets, and e-books.
No one likes to go into those old-fashioned libraries, do they?
Spijkenisse, a sleepy town on the outskirts of Rotterdam hardly worth a quick visit, has the dubious honor of having risen with a record for forgetting.
The population of 80,000 has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counter this shameful situation, some years ago it was decided to contribute in some way to the general culture by copying the seven fictitious bridges depicted on the euro banknotes in the form of decorated reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And so it was that the policy makers decided that there was only one way to improve statistics: a library had to be built!
Winy Maas, of the Dutch architectural firm MVRDV, a master of the art of bar diagrams and responsible for both funny and cynical buildings, took the subject with his usual serenity and attended the presentation of the contest in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And as the jury looked around in perplexity and shrugged, Maas proceeded to stack the books in a pyramidal size and concluded his brief speech with the following words: "Dear fellow citizens:
Here it is, my proposal for the mountain of books in Spijkenisse, the so-called Boekenberg".
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain is rising in the intended place.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is completed with an underground car park, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of apartment buildings and townhouses.
In early November the mountain of books was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus, the small city with no history, which until now had nothing to offer but a postmodern pedestrian zone and an incredibly ugly town hall behind whose white facade one would rather intuit a dairy factory, now has a work of contemporary architecture.
But most importantly, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The long way to the book
The first impression is that it is a book paradise under a cheese grater.
It is true that there is an elevator that takes us right to the center of this mountain range, but true space and reading lovers do not use it, but prefer to merge with its topography at every step of their climb to the top.
The fully glazed interior is bright and easy to see, the recessed brick floor and elegant lanterns unambiguously support the public condition of the library.
The urban environment is perfect.
If you look up, you can see the park benches, the dogs, and the boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
"The bookshelves are usually arranged along the front and in the centre there is a huge dark room, which is usually uncomfortable and impersonal", says Winy Maas.
What we've done is we've turned the classic spatial configuration upside down and taken the reading area from the inside out.
The interior of the mountain is very well used: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education center and the maintenance room.
Special mention is made of the black shelves that serve as wall coverings, parapets and railings at the same time.
The sight, touch and smell are strange.
Even the most up-to-date architects and civil engineers shake their heads when they hear about this unknown material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials", explains Joop Trouborst, project manager in the town of Spijkenisse.
And so one day, on a Frisian farm, we came across the right by-product from agriculture.
For many years, a plastic fabric of a few millimetres thick has been used in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands as a base for holding the roots of crops.
It's a cheap and efficient material.
This fine tissue lasts for two seasons and then is discarded.
For the library, this fabric was pressed, for the first time in such quantities, to four-centimeter-thick plates.
With heat and pressure, so-called agricultural plastic (APP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous, durable material that smells like a mix of a new car and a sneaker.
After 105 steps you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous route of almost 500 meters around the mountain, the reward awaits us. Not only does the café offer a fantastic view of the city, but it also offers delicious Dutch croquettes and their ficus plants in huge pots.
These create a pleasant atmosphere while maintaining the right atmospheric humidity for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a new soul
"While it is hard to believe, given its large glazed surfaces, this building is an exemplary ecological project", says Trouborst.
The necessary heating and cooling is obtained from geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is located under a huge glass pyramid, even on the sunniest days the sun only shines for a few hours inside.
The huge wooden fences that line the glass façade provide shade and absorb most of the sun's rays.
This creates a comfortable indoor climate.
The rest is the thing with the automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the skeptical IT worker, has already dared to set foot in the new library.
And Lisette Verhaig has been there too.
The booklet was also visited by Cynthia Bogarde, a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, who described the "Boekenberg" as Spijkenisse's "late soul".
The reason is that, on the occasion of the opening that took place a couple of weeks ago, all the inhabitants of the city were invited to donate a book from their private collection.
The aim is to fill the gaps in a library which does not yet have a complete archive, currently 70,000 copies.
The concept has gone deep.
The shelves are full.
"There is nothing worse than a half-empty library", says architect Winy Maas.
"I think that thanks to our initiative now all the inhabitants have a certain bond with this building.
Everyone knows that your book is part of the library.
Even if it's just there to adorn.
In this way, the MVRDV studio has achieved a great success in that dominant discipline which in specialized slang is known as "creation of an identity".
The city of Spijkenisse has written a piece of literary history.
No matter how young and uneducated he may be.
Finally a starting point for your identity.
Szabo: 'Germans must play a more leading role'
Germany abstained in the vote on Palestine's admission.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-European relations, this puts Berlin in a rather tricky diplomatic position.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany indicated that it would vote against the proposal to grant the Palestinian territories observer status at the United Nations.
However, Berlin finally abstained.
Why? Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
Now, because of the country's special relationship with Israel, Germany must be careful.
But at the same time I do not think he supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to prove its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
This has finally been declared by NATO.
Does Germany find it difficult to take a clear stance when important international issues are at stake?
Yes, that's right.
This is because at the moment it is reorienting its foreign policy away from a policy led, so to speak, by the United States and towards a German foreign policy.
And what makes things even more difficult is that Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
So the Germans are at a crossroads.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still trying to decide what their role will be, but they have already started the road to a "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy similar to countries like France or Britain.
What exactly does a 'normal' foreign policy mean from the German point of view?
It is a policy which, when it comes to national interests, is willing to defend positions different from those of the United States or its European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is strongly motivated by economic policy, that is to say, by exports and by its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
The German economic interests are to some extent different from those of other great powers and Germany must therefore protect their interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the position taken on the conflict in the Middle East and the UN vote?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf.
For this reason, it must be careful not to alienate itself from Arab public opinion or Arab elites.
This is important, of course.
But I would not put too much emphasis on it, since it is not a totally one-sided relationship.
However, they do play a key role in German considerations.
Has Germany undermined its relationship with the United States by abstaining from voting on important decisions such as the vote on Palestine?
I think that in Europe, and even in the United States, the German position is very well understood.
I therefore believe that there has not been a break as drastic as in the case of Libya.
Perhaps Germany has earned some respect for itself.
In the end, all this has only shown that it is a country which is taken seriously as an international actor and whose interests must be taken into account.
There are different opinions in Europe about the Palestinian initiative.
The US, on the other hand, has been clearly in favour of a veto.
Is there a disparity of opinion between the United States and many European nations?
There have always been these disparities because of US domestic policy.
I think the Obama administration is secretly showing a great deal of understanding of the European position.
But, because of the political situation here, it is obvious that the government cannot defend this position in public.
I think the real disparity of opinion is not really as wide as it is being attributed.
If we look at the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, we see that Obama is not at all enthusiastic about the policies he is developing.
Does Germany find it difficult to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States with the position of its main EU partners?
I think that's precisely what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
It would of course be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and homogeneous European policy, but that is not the case.
They therefore have no possibility of being part of a higher entity, but must push things from their own position.
That is precisely what they are doing now with the euro.
I believe that Germany will play a leading role in the future in forcing Europe to adopt a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, of course, if only because of its relationship with Israel.
This has always been a tricky subject.
But I think the Germans are clear that they must play the role of independent figure.
Does Germany see itself as a major international player?
Or do you still find it difficult to accept that leadership?
Germany is still not used to it, it is always a bit uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for the country to play a more important role.
If we look at the euro crisis, for example, we see that whenever Germany is positioned as a leading player, certain anti-German sentiments are unleashed.
This is not easy for the Germans.
It's an old problem and nobody wants to be surrounded by enemy countries.
In this way Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
You have to show a receptive attitude to different neighbors and opinions and that is not easy.
The US influence in European politics is declining, but the EU is not filling the void at the moment.
The Germans will have no choice but to take on a more leading role.
Even if they don't like it, if it's unpleasant or if it makes them an even more unpopular people, c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is Executive Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institution where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly analyse the challenges facing the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he has specialized in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Brand protection" in China: When Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese brands
Armani is a world-renowned brand and Polo Ralph Lauren is too.
But what is Armani Polo?
Behind this name is a name officially registered in China but which has nothing to do with the original companies.
However, this is protected as long as the true names do not file a claim.
And even then it's not clear that they're going to be given the reason.
"Foreigners are finding it increasingly difficult to protect their brands in China", says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing, specializing in protection rights violations in the Far East.
Every week a new case comes to my desk.
The imitators simply add a couple of letters to register their marks.
In this way, Gucci becomes Lu-Gucci and instead of Prada is registered Prada-Kny.
German companies are also legally copying in the same way, as happened to the sportswear manufacturer Puma.
Pattloch opens a filing cabinet where he keeps seats from the Beijing trademark office.
On 14 September 2010 a Chinese company applied to register the Zegna DF Puma brand, an artificial name also used by the Ermenegildo Zegna fashion house.
It is well known that the Chinese are world champions in copying and infringing on intellectual property rights.
In large cities there are multi-storey department stores dedicated exclusively to the sale of counterfeits.
However, the case of Pattloch is different: on behalf of his clients, he fights against the fact that the trade mark office officially grants Chinese companies the right to profit from a name already registered elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "Bang Ming Pai" or companion brand.
The word originates from the Chinese term "Bang Dakuan",
It refers to women who have "fished" a rich man.
Chinese authorities feel no guilt
"It is harmful to business, we must fight it", Pattloch demands.
"The brand is losing its monopoly position and the image is being damaged".
The financial losses and legal costs for the sectors concerned are in the millions, especially for iconic luxury goods.
According to data from market research firm CLSA, with a volume of EUR 15 billion a year, China is the third largest and fastest growing luxury goods market.
However, the cancellation of entries in the trademark register which are doubtful of their legality is complicated and expensive.
The processes can take up to nine years and the outcome is uncertain.
Pattloch tells of cases where the court dismissed a lawsuit because so much time had passed that the name being sued had already become a "market reality".
"If the plaintiff is unlucky, he may even have to pay the plagiarist money because the lawsuit has damaged the plagiarist's brand in China", Pattloch notes.
Sometimes this is the law of the jungle.
Some of the most well-known cases have to do with graphic elements.
In 2009 Daimler-Benz lost a lawsuit against construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the company that has recently been absorbed by German concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
