Rakfisk is salted trout that is left to ferment in water for, depending on how foul-smelling you prefer, up to a year.
As it gets darker and colder, Norwegians flock to a festival here in Fagernes dedicated to this most, if not the most captivating delicacy.
"You eat it raw and then you drink a glass of aquavit from a sip", says Havard Halvarsen, the city firefighter who is also known as the "General of the Rakfisk", who is in charge of organizing the festival.
Everywhere we look, we see people eating this fish that is kept in small buckets and drinking large amounts of the drink in one gulp.
"Some people prefer aquavit to rakfisk", says Havard.
Drink can kill the smell.
I'll try some pieces.
If you can avoid passing it near your nose, it's not bad; it's not much different from a slice of sushi that you've driven a few miles on a bus.
Rakfisk is a product from a very different time, when poverty was rampant in Norway and before refrigeration, fish was kept in water and salt in airtight barrels during the autumn.
Later, in the middle of winter, when it is well fermented, it is taken out and, evidently with the senses inactive because of alcohol, eaten.
Just a generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work, and they emigrated mainly to the United States.
The population is now growing rapidly; over 13% are immigrants, attracted by the abundance of jobs, high wages and a comprehensive social services system.
A stream of people from Sweden, the old rival and until recently much richer than Norway, is coming to this country to work.
Rakfisk is considered important, an essential, though rather foul-smelling, part of Norway's past.
It's among the most expensive dishes you can buy.
But in fact, everything is expensive. A can of beer or a sandwich costs you a whopping 10 euros ($14) each.
Norway is not usually on the international news agenda and most Norwegians like it that way.
Here people are still reluctant to pronounce the name of Anders Breivik, the far-right racist who shot and killed 77 people, including men, women and children.
Instead, they refer to the shooting as "the July 22 incident".
The Norwegians find it very hard to believe that in their peaceful country one of their own would be capable of such cruelty and murder.
Behind much of Norway's current wealth is the growth, since the early 1970s, of one of the world's largest oil and gas industries.
"But oil is not the only reason we are doing so well", says our waitress Anna, as she passes trays of rakfisk, which with its long blond mane and striking blue eyes represents the image of Norwegian prosperity.
"We are, as you say, a prudent people".
His English, like most people in this country, is impeccable.
"We don't like to brag, we don't like to flaunt".
Norway has managed its oil wealth very carefully; all but a small percentage of the money from this industry is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
While everyone was wasting money they didn't have during the years leading up to the worldwide financial crisis, Norway kept their wallets tight.
"As long as we can ski in the winter and hike in the summer, we are happy", says Anna.
"And eat rakfisk", he adds with a laugh.
I'm in the snow waiting in line to eat something; I've had enough rakfisk.
Now a moose burger is definitely something different and quite juicy to savour.
But at night, that stinking fish comes back.
The hotel I'm staying at is one of many venues that hold a rakfisk dinner where diners vote for the best fish, or perhaps the most testy of the nostrils.
A TV has connected live with a host wearing a birdcage and surrounded by rakfisk plates.
It's like the Eurovision song contest.
"What are your scores for the best fish up there in the mountains, Thor-Juergen?"
"Here's our score, Harvard".
There's laughter and applause.
A man falls from his chair, perhaps overcome by aquavit.
Or maybe it's the fumes from all that fish.
Mexico: Enrique Peña Nieto faces a rough start
As Mexico's incoming President Enrique Peña Nieto prepares to take office, BBC correspondent Will Grant discusses the challenges the new president will face and the different expectations of his people.
Traffic in Mexico City is especially bad right now.
In a city that is already congested at best, a steel fence has been installed since Monday cutting off several of the main roads leading into the city and causing enormous chaos on the roads.
The aim, however, was not to prevent workers from reaching their workplace, but to prevent protesters from reaching the parliament.
On Saturday, the new president of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, will receive the presidential band and assume the management of the nation.
You're facing a complicated task.
Mexico has been making good economic progress under the outgoing government of Felipe Calderón, but the country is mired in a war against drug trafficking that has claimed some 60,000 lives in six years.
"My government has a great commitment to the Mexican people to reduce violence", Mr. Peña Nieto explained earlier this week to U.S. President Barack Obama in the Oval Office.
"I'm going to propose a new security strategy that will allow us to achieve that goal".
Before elbowing the President of the United States, Mr. Peña's previous political experience was as governor of his home state, Mexico.
A highly populated and rapidly growing state, surrounding the capital; opinions about the new leader are divided in this territory where he used to move.
A man of integrity
In the bucolic town of Valle del Bravo, for example, he is fondly remembered.
Its residents credit it with the growth of tourism in the area and the construction of infrastructure.
To get to the city you can drive on one of Mr. Peña Nieto's new roads, which is a huge improvement over the cracked and potholed roads that were rehabilitated.
Plaques bearing his name can also be seen at the entrance to a modern sports complex and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We trust that he will be able to bring about real and lasting change", says his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernández, a deputy from Mr. Peña Nieto's party, the PRI.
"Particularly in terms of security and economy, we look forward to the interesting and real change our country so badly needs".
After an uninterrupted period of 81 years in power, the PRI was ousted by Vicente Fox in 2000.
Deputy Olvera admits that, after 12 years outside the presidential palace of Los Pinos, within the party there are many expectations regarding Enrique Peña Nieto.
It also rejects the opposition's characterization of the new president as being lacking in substance.
"He is a very sincere man, very committed and with an excellent vision of the country.
He is a fantastic statesman and, above all, a good listener".
However, across the state that's not the impression many people have of their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast to the cobbled streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
Hidden beneath highway sections, it is, in many ways, a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems of the municipality are also hard and urban.
Earlier this year, the military was called in to help fight the drug gangs operating in the neighborhoods and violence against women is especially severe.
In a desert plot next to a landfill, the bodies of dozens of murdered women have been abandoned in the last two years alone.
More than 1,000 women were murdered in the state of Mexico while Mr. Peña Nieto was governor, a much higher rate than Ciudad Juarez, unfortunately famous for its violence and a place that is synonymous with the murder of innocent women.
Mr. Peña Nieto's critics say, at best, he failed to address the problem of femicide while in office.
His most vocal critics accuse his administration of turning a blind eye.
In a concrete house, typical of the decaying neighborhood, Irinea Buendía has to make efforts to hold back tears while showing me photographs of her deceased daughter, Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of events, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
However, her family believes her partner killed her.
"When I arrived at her home, it looked as if her body had been cleaned", recalls Mrs. Buendía.
"There were signs that she had been beaten and rigor mortis had already appeared".
As her mother tells the story, a photograph of Mariana watches from the walls, next to a cross on which a single word is read: Justice.
However, that's exactly what the family says has been denied.
"The state authorities have treated me as if I were an old gossip, a troublemaker, a complainer.
They want you to just take what they say and shut up".
"But that cannot be the case when there have been so many irregularities and so much neglect", he says.
The presidential band that President Peña Nieto will receive on Saturday will come with a huge responsibility.
Tens of thousands of families have been affected by violent crime in Mexico over the past six years and the new president has promised to make it a priority during his term.
"I hope he is the same kind of president he was when he was governor", says PRI deputy Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
However, that is precisely what the families of the victims of Ciudad Neza fear most.
Bradley Manning didn't report any ill-treatment, according to prosecutors.
Prosecutors are trying to deal with allegations of abuse by Bradley Manning during his time in prison.
The trial focuses on Manning's time at Quantico Military Prison in Virginia.
The defense wants the case dismissed on the basis that Manning's incarceration was severe.
The army soldier is accused of stealing thousands of classified documents.
Prosecutors sought to prove Friday that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of classified information in U.S. history, missed multiple opportunities to expose the mistreatment he now alleges he suffered while in military custody.
During the interrogation of Manning by the prosecution at a pretrial hearing at Ft. Meade, Maryland, Prosecutor Commander Ashden Fein stated that records of weekly visits by officers from the unit that Manning received during his nine months in custody at Quantico, Virginia, show no complaints about the treatment he received.
The interrogation, which took place during a hearing following the defense's request that the case be dismissed on the grounds that his imprisonment had been harsh and that it had already resulted in sufficient punishment, came a day after Manning testified that he had contemplated suicide while in custody.
The Army intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of classified documents while on duty in Iraq.
WikiLeaks later published the material on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of the information.
At Friday's hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms that officers filled out after Manning's visits during his arrest at Quantico Military Prison, where he was held in maximum security from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers would have asked Manning questions and noted down his answers.
When asked about the forms by Fein on Friday, Manning acknowledged that he had described the treatment he received from the guards as "excellent" and the treatment he received at the facility in general as "very professional".
The forms show no complaints of ill-treatment, even though officers asked Manning directly about the treatment he was receiving, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns about some issues and that the visiting officers had discussed those issues and indicated that they would be addressed, but that they did not record those issues in the record.
"They wrote 'no incidents' (after having spoken about the problems) but this does not necessarily mean that I had not mentioned any problems", Manning said.
The judge, Army Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why she had not reported the treatment she received during the January 2011 meeting with a council tasked with examining suicide intentions she had expressed in a form months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during that meeting was to obtain a reduction in the "injury prevention" regime under which he was.
The military said they had put him under that restrictive regime, which is one degree below suicide watch, to ensure his protection and the safety of others.
"I wanted the staff to know that I was fine and (wanted) to stop being on injury prevention... so I could enjoy what, from my point of view, is a better quality of life", Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the military prison at the Marine Corps base at Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and that on one occasion he fainted from the heat.
He said that the fact that he wasn't allowed to know what was happening to him or what was happening in the outside world was very distressing.
"My world was reduced to just Camp Arafjon, to that cage", Manning explained Thursday.
"I thought I was going to die in that cage".
Manning claimed that, once transferred to Quantico, he spent most days in a small cell, at least for 21 hours and often for 23 hours, without company.
Manning said he was only allowed to have a mattress, a blanket, slippers, some clothes and his glasses.
He explained that he tried to move all the time, since it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
Manning claimed that he always had a light coming from outside pointing at his eyes while he slept.
He said if the guards couldn't see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up to turn around again.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint in January 2011 about Manning's treatment.
Manning was transferred to the military prison at Fort Leavenworth in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation he made in Thursday's deposition that after being forced to sleep naked one night in his Quantico cell, he was forced during a morning count to stand naked in front of the jail guards and other inmates.
Manning had testified that he had never been given the opportunity to cover himself with the blanket during the count.
During the judge's questioning on Friday, Manning said he deduced from the order given him by the janitor that he should drop the blanket he might have covered himself with, but he acknowledged that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before in an attempt to prove to an officer that he posed no danger to himself.
Manning claimed that he had told the officer that he could have used the rubber band from his underwear or his slippers to injure himself but that he had not.
Manning testified that that night his underwear, flip-flops and glasses were removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope the judge will at least take into account his experiences during his time in prison and drastically reduce his sentence if he is convicted at the court-martial, which is scheduled to begin early next year.
The defense said it plans to have Manning plead guilty to misdemeanors and defend other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is scheduled to resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has maintained that Manning was held in accordance with the rules applicable to all detainees in maximum custody at Quantico.
The charges against Manning include cooperation with the enemy, illegal solicitation of information on the Internet, leaking of national defense information, and theft of public property or records.
If found guilty on all charges, you could face life in prison.
My Mexican-American identity crisis
He says many were forced to leave Mexico due to lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to criticize those who left; he says they remind Mexicans of those difficult times
Navarrette comments that Mexican-Americans are caught between two worlds.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had barely come down the esplanade and reached the immigration processing area and was already totally confused.
Signs pointed the way to two lines, one for "Mexicans" and one for "Foreigners".
I stood there for a few seconds not sure where I was going.
Having grown up in Central California, all my life I've been called "Mexican".
It's ethnic shorthand, just like my friends in Boston refer to themselves as "Irish" or my friends in New York call themselves "Italian".
Later I decided on "Mexican-American".
But this was Mexico.
And, in my grandfather's homeland, shorthand or script was not necessary.
He was simply American.
I speak Spanish, well enough to handle an interview in this language.
But I don't have the vocabulary of a native speaker and I can't shake my American accent.
So I took my American passport and I got in line for foreigners.
I thought about that moment this week when the president-elect of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
The agenda for the day, as always when the leaders of these two countries meet, was: immigration, drugs and trade.
Peña Nieto was also eager to talk about the growth of the Mexican economy, one of the reasons why at this time it is as likely for a Mexican to stay in Mexico as to venture to the United States.
It wants to associate with the United States and Canada and create a trade bloc in North America in the style of the European Union.
In addition, Peña Nieto promised to continue fighting drug cartels in Mexico, though he did not give details.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is complicated and full of rancor.
Most Americans probably never remember that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to cede half their territory at gunpoint.
But for Mexicans, who think in centuries, not minutes, the elements that remind them of it are everywhere.
So the moment a U.S. official says anything that involves the slightest criticism of Mexico, you start hearing complaints, both in the press and among the Mexican elite, about how the Americans are usurping the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And the sons of Moctezuma are on the war footing.
And yet, for Mexico, the relationship that really poses a challenge is the one they have with the more than 35 million Mexican-Americans living in the United States.
Are we talking about grudges?
There's a lot of it.
In Mexico there are winners and losers, people for whom the country provides opportunities and others for whom it does not.
The only reason there are so many people of Mexican descent living in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is because, at some point in our family tree, there was a person, maybe a father or a mother or one of the grandparents, who was shut out of opportunities in Mexico and had to march north.
And most of the time, that person fit a certain profile: dark skin, low education, from a poor village, etc.
We are their descendants and we are loyal to them.
Not to Mexico.
And, even though we may be living the American dream now, having gone to good schools and having had good jobs, we can never lose sight of that, the American dream, and not the Mexican dream.
Our identity may sometimes be unclear, but our loyalty is.
It's for the United States.
We are also aware that many of the Mexican ruling class elite do not like us.
The feeling is mutual.
They see us as a reminder of a humiliating defeat and look over our shoulder as if we were of a lower category that is not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough and our ties to Mexico will never be strong enough.
In their view, our existence is synonymous with failure.
If our families hadn't failed in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
And now we wouldn't be trapped behind this silk curtain, living well in America but still, lonely souls.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and came to the United States legally as a child, reminds me that there is this friction between Mexicans and Mexican-Americans because the former know more solidly who they are and the latter are bothered by it.
Although she is a citizen of the United States, she considers herself part of both countries.
Meanwhile, many Mexican-Americans I know feel like they're not part of either.
We love listening to the Mexican group Los Tigres del Norte, but also to Bruce Springsteen.
You have the best of each country, but you're not rooted in any of them.
In Mexico, we're seen as Americans.
And in the United States, we're considered Mexican.
Now, to complicate matters even more, from what I learned during my trip, some Mexican leaders and some intellectuals want to reconnect with the diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to work as makeshift "ambassadors" for Mexico, representing their interests in the United States.
We would tell our fellow Americans how fantastic it is to visit that country and we would pressure political leaders to strengthen their ties with Mexico.
Yes, of course.
That's not gonna happen.
There's too much grudge.
And with wage inequality, rampant corruption and drug violence, many of us are not so sure it's a fantastic country.
I'm afraid you're gonna be left alone with this idea, friends.
It's only fair.
If some Mexicans are still not ready to forgive the United States for the way they treated Mexico a century and a half ago, then they have to accept the fact that some Mexican-Americans are still resentful for how their relatives were treated much less recently.
I'm not going to.
Maybe we're more "Mexican" than I thought.
Old battles, new middle east
A ceasefire between Israel and Hamas may well be an unlikely basis for peace.
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
Another bloodshed that seems to indicate that all hope is in vain.
Amid the useless and habitual arguments over who started first, piles of buildings have been reduced to rubble; over 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed and, for the first time, missiles from Gaza have fallen near Tel Aviv, the metropolis of Israel, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But even though Israelis and Palestinians seem to be anchored in their old conflict, everything around them in the Middle East is changing.
The Arab Spring has left everything in pieces whether you like it or not, Palestinians and Israelis have been caught in the regional upheaval.
Perhaps this will make their fight even bloodier than before.
However, there is reason to believe that their deadly stalemate could be breaking.
A War Neither Lost Nor Won
At first glance, optimism seems very difficult to justify at present.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on November 21 is maintained, this week's fighting has strengthened the hawks on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has ruled Gaza since 2007, will claim to have forced the Israelis to withdraw, even though Gaza has been beaten up.
And despite killing some of its leaders and putting pressure on the 1.7 million people of Gaza in one of the most miserable and densely populated corners of the planet, Israel has not been able to wipe out Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, the other side of Palestine currently ruled by its ruthless rivals Fatah, the more moderate Palestinian faction.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may conclude that time is on their side.
As Islamists have gained influence throughout the Arab world, Hamas has made rich and powerful friendships.
Turkey, a rising regional power that had previously been Israel's closest Muslim ally, has embraced the cause of Hamas, as has Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic Gulf states.
Exultant Hamas members say the Islamist crescent is encircling Israel, from Lebanon in the north, where the Hezbollah militia-party dominates, through Syria, where rebels of an increasingly Islamist bent could topple Bashar Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies are threatening the king.
Especially on the southern flank of Israel, the growth of the Muslim Brotherhood led by President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt, by far the most populous and fundamental of the Arab countries, has changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the secular despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, didn't have much time for Hamas.
The Muslim Brotherhood, on the other hand, is cousin to Hamas and its leaders are more dependent on popular opinion.
In future diplomatic actions, Hamas may emerge as a protagonist that cannot be excluded, not even Israel and the United States.
Meanwhile, the hard-line Israel will draw the opposite conclusion.
As far as the military question is concerned, they have put Hamas in its place.
Israel's Iron Dome anti-missile system has proven its effectiveness and many of Hamas' missiles have been destroyed.
The Israelis will sleep better... for a while.
As for diplomacy, the United States is more assertive than ever; many European countries also blamed Hamas for starting the latest wave of violence.
First of all, Israel has prospered, especially under the government of Benjamin Netanyahu, a prime minister who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets fired from Gaza have claimed the lives of about 30 Israelis since 2004, Israel has not had too many suicide bombers, thanks in part to the barrier that corrodes the West Bank, the main piece of territory aspiring to become a Palestinian state, and protects Jewish settlements that continue to grow despite being illegal under international law.
Mr Netanyahu, whose Likud party has joined an even more hardline group led by Avigdor Lieberman in the run-up to the January 22 elections, is in a good position.
Why spoil those twisted Palestinians by giving them a state of their own?
If they really ruled in the West Bank, wouldn't they fire rockets like their compatriots have in Gaza?
Better to get them behind that wall and give them a good punch if they raise their heads.
The hard-liners may prevail, though the Arab Spring may alter their calculations.
Although the Islamists who take power in Egypt and elsewhere may not have much appreciation for Israel, their priority will be to address internal difficulties.
Israel's defense budget is greater than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
Starting a war with the superpower in the region will hardly help the new Arab governments improve their economies.
That the pragmatic Mr. Morsi has worked with Barack Obama to get the ceasefire is a good omen and could mark the beginning of something.
The Israelis should also think long-term.
With the rest of the Arab world becoming more democratic, depriving the Palestinians of their right to self-determination is creating a powder keg that will one day explode in the Israeli-occupied territories, just as a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
The repression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state and demographics are worsening as the Arab population increases.
The bloody missions against Gaza every two or three years to repel Hamas will pay an increasing diplomatic toll.
Both sides need a push from people outside the conflict.
The solution is still what sensible people on both sides, most of the outside world and this newspaper are advocating: two states and the ceding of territory by Israel for security reasons.
The hope, small in the short term, is that the ceasefire will give a little more momentum to the outsiders who are fighting for this cause.
Egypt, which must start curbing the flow of arms into Gaza, along with Turkey and Qatar, is in an unprecedented position to convince Hamas to accept the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, with land exchanges and a shared Jerusalem.
The Arabs who are not involved should also pressure Hamas and Fatah to join.
That would contribute more to the creation of a Palestinian state than the imminent attempt to obtain a virtual statehood category at the UN.
Mr Obama also has an important role to play in getting Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term he failed to present his own peace plan.
Back at the White House, he seems just as reluctant to give you his attention.
This attitude is a deplorable vision of the future.
A stable Middle East is of vital interest to the United States.
This implies a peace agreement between Israel and Palestine.
The law on tobacco packaging goes into effect in Australia
Warnings about the dangers of smoking and ill-healthy body parts appear on a dull green box, which is the same for all brands of tobacco
Australia's world-first tobacco and generic packaging law comes into force, replacing the logos and brand colors with a pale olive green wrapper, gruesome images of ill body parts and depictions of sick children and babies from smoking parents.
Apart from the various images and health warnings, the only difference between the boxes, which are mandatory from Saturday, are the brand names, all printed in a small typeface.
It is the most stringent regulation in the world on tobacco packaging.
The federal government of Australia says that the goal is to discourage youths from smoking by eliminating the traits that make the habit glamorous.
He trusts studies that show that if a person has not started smoking before age 26, there is a 99 percent chance he will never do so.
"You can see that children, even from a very young age, understand the message that the tobacco company is trying to sell through its brand", said Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that showed, for example, how girls related the logo of a crown to the idea of being a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and these changes will not affect the profits of multinationals too much, other countries are considering similar measures.
The tobacco industry has put enormous pressure on the law.
Tobacco companies claimed that the law would encourage the black market in tobacco, where cigarettes would be cheaper and more accessible.
"The legislation will have serious unintended consequences", said Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco in Australia.
It will increase the amount of tobacco that counterfeiters from China and Indonesia will bring in to sell on the streets of Australia.
Other people say their business has benefited after the law was passed.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, said demand for silicone snuff bottles and covers to cover up the nasty images of the cartons had skyrocketed almost from zero two months ago, when British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost a recusal to the law in Australia's Supreme Court.
Ms. Ha claimed that Zico had sold up to 6,000 units to wholesale establishments and was expecting more stocks.
"It's a good business for us".
According to experts, the potential obstacle is the popularity of social networks among the demographic sector targeted by the plan.
Following a series of Australian laws banning television advertising and sports sponsorship and requiring most retailers not to display cigarettes, tobacco marketing has moved to online.
Australia has banned advertising on the Internet to local companies and websites, but cannot restrict it to foreign websites.
"If you're a tobacco marketer and you only have this little window to promote your products, the online space is the most compelling place to be", said Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman noted an increase in brand reviews from "ordinary citizens" posted on social media websites like YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
One wonders if it is just a private citizen who really loves Marlboro cigarettes and has taken the trouble to make a video or if some marketing company is behind it all.
British American Tobacco of Australia indicated that the industry is focusing more on what the new regulations imply than on marketing.
The industry has even paid for Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to object to the new rules; these countries are claiming to the World Trade Organization that trade is being unfairly restricted, even though none of these countries have a significant volume of trade with Australia.
The WTO is likely to issue a resolution in mid-2013.
Plibersek said the government had held talks with other countries that are considering similar tobacco packaging laws.
In 2001, Canada became the first country to make it mandatory to include images in the box.
They are currently compulsory in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
In Britain, New Zealand, South Africa and India, tougher laws are being considered.
In Australia many smokers are defiant.
"Photographs do not affect me.
I just ignore them".
"You take the cigarette and put the pack away", says Victor El Hage as he buys a pack with a picture of a tumor in his mouth.
"Honestly, there's only one reason I would quit: for my daughter".
James Yu, manager of the King of the Pack pond in central Sydney, says that the uniform boxes make it harder for him to put them on the shelves.
"It used to take me an hour to unpack a delivery; now it takes me four", says Yu.
"The government should have banned tobacco altogether and then, there it is, okay, it's over and we close the store", he says as he raises his hands.
In a world that's constantly connected, it's not so bad to get a little bored.
During this year's Thanksgiving holiday, I unexpectedly had to spend five hours at an airport because the plane we were flying in had a mechanical problem and we had to wait for another plane to arrive.
So I had a lot of time to think about the boredom.
I'm not gonna lie to you guys.
Spending half a day at an airport waiting for a flight is pretty boring, even if you have the means to be entertained, like books, magazines or iPhones, not to mention duty-free shops.
But there are more and more academics and child development experts who extol the benefits of boredom.
They say that it is okay for us and our children to get bored from time to time.
Boredom forces the brain to look for interesting options and may encourage creativity.
Since most of us are currently connected to this or that screen, we do not experience the benefits of boredom.
So should we accept boredom in a good mood?
- I know.
And no, you didn't.
But we'll talk about it later.
First, like many people, I assumed that, now that we have more time for leisure, boredom would be a relatively recent phenomenon.
But as Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary, Canada, and author of the book "Boredom: A Lively History" published in 2011 by Yale University Press, says, this is not the case.
"In fact, the history of boredom is very long", he says.
On the walls of Pompeii there are Latin graffiti about boredom dating back to the first century AD.
We also need to think about how we define boredom.
"The problem is that it has been defined and discussed in a wide variety of ways", says John D. Eastwood, professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After reviewing published research and pitching the idea to a discussion group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as the experience of "wanting, but not being able, to participate in an activity that fills you".
He says the difference between boredom and apathy is that a person does not do something but wants to do it.
He points out that with apathy there is no desire to do anything.
The main experience of boredom, he says, is "the altered attentional process, associated with a low mood and a sense of slow motion".
Boredom can sound terribly like depression.
