Some groups listened in the next room to a TV program at full volume that had no relationship, others listened at low volume, so that it was barely noticeable, while the third group did not hear the audio at all.
The group who listened to the program at a low volume showed more boredom than the other two groups; they had trouble concentrating, but they were not sure why and attributed it to boredom.
"When you try to concentrate on a difficult or interesting task, distracted attention can lead to boredom", said Mark J. Fenske, professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph, Ontario, and one of the study's authors.
