Unasur summit ends without making public the Lima Declaration
The VI Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) concluded today in Peru without the Lima Declaration being made public, previously announced and theoretically signed by the seven attending leaders.
Efe tried repeatedly to access the document signed at the VI Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but sources from the Cancillery and Presidency initially said they would hand it over after the closure, but later said it would be published on the Peruvian Government's website.
When asked about the text, they pointed out that the content had been exposed by the president of Peru, Ollanta Humala, during brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information from the Summit was restricted at all times.
During the day, only the video of the presidential assembly without sound was broadcast in the press room with the message "private session, audio restricted".
The little information that circulated among reporters was delivered by press spokesmen from some of the governments of the UNASUR attending the meeting, although not the Peruvian one.
The only document released during the day was the list of presidents attending, which caused the discomfort of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more data.
The Peruvian presidency subsequently sent an email to the media with the summit's "final statement", but it is Humala's pronouncement, not the official document that closed the summit.
In October last year, Peru hosted the III South America-Arab States Summit (ASPA), and despite press demands, the Lima Declaration, which had been announced earlier, was not published.
The official website of ASPA confirms that the document was published on Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities made efforts to ensure secure transmission systems for all journalists but limited information gathering to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to accept a ruling by the Hague Court to settle a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional summit and ratified that they will respect the decision of the (CIJ), which begins Monday in The Hague to hear the allegations of both sides, in the process Lima presented against Santiago.
"We will take and execute the sentence that defines the differences that we are bringing to this international court today", Humala said, along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has been, is and will continue to be a country respectful of international law, of the peaceful solution of disputes, of treaties and international courts", added Piñera, and greeted Humala with a handshake, beside the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation of both presidents that they will submit to the ICJ came after Colombia denounced this week the Pact of Bogotá by which it had agreed to submit to the rulings of that international tribunal, after a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it considered seriously erroneous.
The summit was held with the absences of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chávez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the removal of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was in charge of opening the morning deliberations and closing the summit, shortly after noon in Lima.
The President read the final document in which he informed that 16 agreements were adopted and the lines of action were set for 31 projects between the South American countries for a total of 17 billion dollars in investments.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the UNASUR countries will make "important steps towards the goal of a South American citizenship for which we are expanding the agreements on residence".
He said that actions are being taken to improve "cooperation in the fight against citizen insecurity and transnational organized crime, actions to make medicines more accessible, access to low-cost internet in all corners of South America, and jointly and efficiently address the risks of natural disasters".
With Europe in crisis, "economic consolidation (of Latin America) must not have a triumphalist matrix but must serve to expand our productive matrix and foreshadow a better future for our peoples", Humala added.
"We have decided to privilege a group of 31 emblematic projects that will improve the connection of the spaces of South America, especially in rural areas and borders...uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits", the Peruvian president said in a message read.
Among those projects, he mentioned that five correspond to Peru, and are located in the transverse axes of their territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two point to a greater connection with Ecuador, although he did not give more details.
The final document also mentioned the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in that country will serve to reincorporate it into the Union of South American Nations", from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and with good relations between neighbours was another of the issues underlined by the summit.
In this regard, the president of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before starting his participation in the regional summit that he hoped to meet with his Nicaragua counterpart, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico to treat respectfully the maritime dispute after a ruling by the CIJ, questioned by Bogotá.
"Tomorrow (Saturday) I may have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega", Santos said.
"We are going to review all these roads, they are not exclusive, including the treaty with Nicaragua will require a conversation with Nicaragua", he stressed.
"With President Ortega I hope I can tell him that we handle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible", Santos added.
Santos and Ortega would meet on Saturday in Mexico where they plan to attend the taking of command of the new president of that country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
The EU's defence ministers also met to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus on defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the latter is suspended.
Peru holds the provisional presidency of the regional bloc.
