They're starting a course exploring the "End of the World"
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to teach a course on the end of the world, he knew he had an irresistible hook: The end of the Mayan Calendar's "long countdown" on December 21, which many people have held on to as proof that the end of the world is coming.
But Charmé had no idea what lay ahead in the next couple of months: the cataclysmic Hurricane Sandy, a fiscal cliff that some have called "two-armageddon", and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where Christian end-time theorists believe the apocalypse will begin.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever", Charmé told students at Rutgers-Camden University in New Jersey this week.
If you look at what's been happening in the world today as if we were 30 days away and counting, this has been a really good period.
And remember, bad is good for those with an apocalyptic mindset.
And he's not the only professor who's offering courses on the "end of the world" this semester, theoretically the last in history.
At Temple, Associate Professor Barry Vacker is teaching the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World".
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
"We look at why these ideas proliferate over time", he said, and how they offer hypothetical scenarios that guide certain human behavior.
If nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, for example, war could break out.
This month students analyzed films with apocalyptic themes and explored how they compare to real-life examples.
"I've tried to inform students about what's possible, probable, credible and impossible", Vacker said.
On the main campus of Penn State University, Latin American History professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an associate professor of Art History and Anthropology, have teamed up to teach a course, titled simply "The End of the World".
"We don't add '2012' so we always have the option of teaching the course again, in case the world doesn't end", Restall said.
Despite the "imminent ruin", students must study, generate projects and take final exams.
At Penn State, the final exam will be taken on the eve of the Apocalypse, leaving students no choice but to work "until the very night the world is supposed to end", Restall said.
The courses proved quite popular.
"It saturated in two hours", Restall said of his course for high-achieving students, which was filled with 35 students.
We got emails for weeks and weeks before the semester started from people asking if there was still room.
The students, on the other hand, say that the course is one of the most interesting.
"I find it fascinating to see what people do to comfort themselves", said Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old religion and sociology major student from Haddonfield, New Jersey, at Rutgers-Camden.
And it is that the apocalyptic mentality, secular or religious, is just a matter of comfort or lack of it.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old student majoring in psychology and nursing, said he has seen all the apocalyptic movies.
"I've never heard of a class that could teach that", he said.
I enjoy it.
But no student interviewed - let alone a teacher - said he believed in the December 21 expiration date.
"Our first project was about Mayan prophecy and we kind of discredited it", said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old senior at Temple from West Chester.
The Mayans never predicted the end of the world; it's just a key point on the calendar, Restall said.
But he noted that there is an apocalyptic anxiety in Western culture, going back several centuries, in which people react to changes around them by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has caused a boom in these speculations.
"Otherwhere people don't think about this", he said.
Mostly in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a religion professor at La Salle University who is teaching courses in the Philippines this year, quickly answered the question of whether he knew of any courses on the "end of the world" there.
"The Philippines is not involved in the end of the world", he wrote, hinting at an exception from a higher authority.
We have a pardon from the Pope.
Restall noted that over the years there has been much talk of the final judgment days, and he said that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will immediately start thinking about the next date" or philosophizing that December 21 is the beginning of a seven-year period after which the world will end.
Students and teachers are taking the date lightly.
Several said they plan to go to "end of the world" parties.
"Maybe I'll call some friends and have a laugh", said 20-year-old communications student Samira Ford.
